<paragraph blockId="1.[826,1441,1788,1902]" lastBlockId="2.[144,759,863,1099]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="209" pageId="1" pageNumber="208">
<emphasis box="[826,943,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="208">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
A large basal ornithuromorph bird that can be distinguished from other ornithuromorphs by the unique combination of the following features: V-shaped furcula with a short hypocleidium; sternum bearing elongated lateral trabecula with fan-shaped distal expansion; broad cranial margin of sternum with obtuse angle defined by coracoidal sulci of 113°; manual claws nearly straight; proximal ends of metatarsals II– IV coplanar; metatarsal IV robust (autapomorphy); hallucal ungual reduced; and intermebral index (humerus + ulna + carpometacarpus/
</paragraph>
